            <button class="w-full text-left p-6 font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-slate-50 flex justify-between items-center" data-faq-toggle>
              Can I upgrade existing weeping tile to French drain?
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
              <p>Yes, but it requires full excavation and removal of existing tiles. Most contractors recommend complete replacement for optimal performance. The process involves excavating to footing level, removing old tiles and stone, and installing a new French drain system with proper filtration.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white  shadow-md border-2 border-slate-100">
            <button class="w-full text-left p-6 font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-slate-50 flex justify-between items-center" data-faq-toggle>
              Which system works better in Toronto's climate?
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
              <p>French drains perform better in Toronto's freeze-thaw cycles. The continuous pipe system is less susceptible to frost heaving, and the geotextile fabric prevents soil migration during spring thaw. Weeping tiles can separate at joints during freeze-thaw cycles.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white  shadow-md border-2 border-slate-100">
            <button class="w-full text-left p-6 font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-slate-50 flex justify-between items-center" data-faq-toggle>
              How often should each system be maintained?
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
              <p>French drains: Professional cleaning every 5-7 years. Weeping tiles: Inspection every 2-3 years, cleaning every 3-5 years. Weeping tiles require more frequent maintenance due to joint separation and debris accumulation at tile connections.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white  shadow-md border-2 border-slate-100">
            <button class="w-full text-left p-6 font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-slate-50 flex justify-between items-center" data-faq-toggle>
              What are the signs that my drainage system is failing?
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
              <p>Common failure signs include: water infiltration after heavy rain, efflorescence on foundation walls, musty odors in basement, soggy areas around foundation perimeter, and visible settlement or cracking near the foundation. Both systems show similar failure symptoms.</p>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="bg-white  shadow-md border-2 border-slate-100">
            <button class="w-full text-left p-6 font-semibold text-lg hover:bg-slate-50 flex justify-between items-center" data-faq-toggle>
              Are there building code requirements for drainage systems?
              <svg class="w-5 h-5 transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"/>
              </svg>
            </button>
            <div class="hidden px-6 pb-6">
              <p>Yes, Ontario Building Code requires foundation drainage systems for all new construction. Both French drains and weeping tiles meet code requirements when properly installed. French drains often exceed minimum standards and are preferred by most modern contractors.</p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
